column2:
Adds a new POST endpoint "/quality/perftest" which consumes a "PerfTestDataCreateRequest.java" model to post Perf results in Cucumber Json format.

The new endpoint allows 3rd party performance testing applications to post KPI (Key Performance indicator) metrics which out the need for a Jenkins build.

"runId" property on PerfTestDataCreateRequest should be unique for every test execution. 
Unique names for "testName" and "perfTool" properties will create a new collector Item, under which a new Test result record would be added.

11/13/2017-- Audit API work added along with audit status
column5: changes for adding POST endpoint to add Perf results and Perf Audit API endpoint

re-upgrade docker-compose to v2
column11:
340237319 @virtualpeter thanks.
i'm happy to further upgrade this to v3.2/swarm as the next step after this is merged üòÅ  rbtr
353121980 @rbtr @satishc1 - I think we should not merge this PR for two reasons:
1: we need to overhaul the docker-compose file. Currently it tries to do way too much. I think it should be split up into a "core" file which creates and connects the UI, api, and db and then each collector should have it's own file that extends the core file. 
2: this PR is sloppy. It has white space issues, inconsistent image naming, and development trash is left in
I get that this wasn't supposed to be an upgrade and was just intended to recapture the 'clobbered' changes but I can't imagine merging this one without a follow up PR and I don't think that's worth the time when we really need to change the entire file in the near future anyway. matthewbeasley
353123136 @matthewbeasley Agreed. No point merging a sloppy pr done just for the sake of recapturing  'clobbered' changes. Thanks. satishc1
353419775 @matthewbeasley 
to 1.  If you want to say that this isn't worth merging because the whole compose file needs to be scrapped and redone, fine, but let's be clear that this changeset only puts things back have been removed accidently. 

Which brings me to 2.  I evidently didn't make myself clear enough. I didn't write any code in this PR. All of this was already in master at several points in the history. This cleanup was done just in git, to consolidate and put back changes that had already been **approved and merged** but were then undone by a later merge with an earlier root commit.

 rbtr
353430279 @rbtr - believe me, you‚Äôve made it very clear that you didn‚Äôt do any original work in this PR. We really appreciate your interest in this project and if you would like to submit a separate PR that targets compose v3 or even recaptures the changes cleanly we would love to review that, but as stated above we don‚Äôt feel that it is worth it to merge this one.  matthewbeasley
340236931 i think the only change relevant to me was the appdynamics collector. i have checked that and it seems ok.

overall I think its time to refactor the dockerfiles and docker-compose to support running in docker swarm or kubernetes environments and that it is time to review how env variables and the collector properties scripts are used - the pattern is working ok, but is at odds with newer docker secrets / docker config.

For now though it is a good start to move away from v1 and its implied ENV variable sharing between containers so Im in favour of this change virtualpeter

I am trying to build Hygieia on an Ubuntu 16.04 machine. I have tried cloning the Hygieia repostory, ensuring that I am on the master branch and that everything is up to date, then running `mvn clean install package`. The build fails.

It gives the following error message:
```
Results :

Failed tests: 
  DefaultSecurityTest.registerUser:87 Status expected:<200> but was:<401>

Tests run: 287, Failures: 1, Errors: 0, Skipped: 3

[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------
[INFO] Reactor Summary:
[INFO] 
[INFO] com.capitalone.dashboard:Hygieia ................... SUCCESS [  0.655 s]
[INFO] com.capitalone.dashboard:core ...................... SUCCESS [ 20.098 s]
[INFO] com.capitalone.dashboard:api ....................... FAILURE [ 11.775 s]
```

The machine is running the following software:
```
Apache Maven 3.5.2
Java version: 1.8.0_151, vendor: Oracle Corporation
```
I was expecting this to be a software version issue, or for there to be something missing from my system. However, as far as I can tell, the Hygieia documentation only states Java 1.8 as a requirement.

I can get the build to succeed if I check out the tag `Hygieia-2.0.4`, but not on master.

Am I missing something?

column2:
Use the "statuses_url" provided by the pull request API response.

"statuses_url" points to /repos/:owner/:repo/statuses/:ref which
returns all commit statuses for a given ref.

/repos/:owner/:repo/commits/:ref/status is more convenient it
returns the most recent status for each context. This is ok. We can
calculate the most recent status from /repos/:owner/:repo/statuses/:ref.

Using /repos/:owner/:repo/statuses/:ref also contains the "creator"
property for the commit status. This information isn't used at the
moment but will become useful when GitHub Apps adoption is
more widespread.
column5: Bug fix for GitHub fetch commit statuses.

column2:
Is there anyway we can setup Role based access to Dashboard. Right now, people can see the dashboard/widgets without signup to dashboard.

We want to restrict the visibility of the dashboard/widgets based on Role like Product Manager, Team Lead, Developer and so on.

Is this something possible in Hygieia Dashboard?If yes, can you please guide me.

Regards,
Raghav
column5: Role based access in UI Dashboard
column11: 340803134 @sraghu-rs - Only two roles available at present - ViewOnly and Owner. Admin and owner of dashboard can add multiple owners for a dashboard. If you want to restrict view for All Dashboards, you have to do a work around in code. In site.html add ng-show="ctrl.showAuthentication" on below LOC nireeshT 358863962 @nireeshT -- the suggestion you had given is to add above code Only two roles available at present - ViewOnly and Owner. Admin and owner of dashboard can add multiple owners for a dashboard. If you want to restrict view for All Dashboards, you have to do a work around in code. In site.html add ng-show="ctrl.showAuthentication" on below LOC works only when logout If i create a new user with no access and after login he is able to see all dashboard in readonly mode which i want to ristrict pls your inputs on the same kagasa

I'm trying to get a local prototype going, and I'd prefer to either disable the authentication altogether, or have it at least running from the local database instead of LDAP/AD. Is that easily doable? Documented anywhere?

There's a signup screen in the UI, so I'm assuming this should work somehow?

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1946435/31848064-70808872-b5de-11e7-893f-93dfafc65b19.png)

Thanks in advance for any pointers.

column2:
Tests peer review using either GitHub commit statuses or GitHub reviews. If the Hygieia API settings are populated with a list of peer review contexts then test the commit statuses.  When a commit status with a matching context is found, then use the state of the commit status to indicate peer review. If the Hygieia API settings do not have a peer review context then do not use the commit status.

When no peer review commit status is found then fallback to using GitHub Reviews. Check for at least one approved review. GitHub Reviews does not allow self-review. Closes #1735

Thanks,

column2:
Hi all,
I had a question about the Hygieia-Jenkins plugin. During setup on the Jenkins machine you provide it with a Hygieia API url so the plugin knows where to push the data. I have multiple teams on a single jenkins machine and they each want to  stand up their own instance of the Hygieia Dashboard. Is there a way to provide multiple Hygieia API urls on one jenkins machine?

thanks!

column11:
332565020 @kavalpatel15 : what do you mean by own instance of Hygieia Dashboard. Do you mean own dashboard or own instance of Hygieia stack (api, DB, and UI).  nitin1706
332602572 They would like their own instance of the Hygieia stack. kavalpatel15
332948291 It will not be possible to send data to multiple Hygieia instances from same jenkins server. 
Hygieia-Jenkins plugin is configured at Jenkins server level and it can send data only to one Hygieia instance.
You can configure to have one Hygieia instance shared across teams and each team having their own dashboard. nitin1706

column2:
I think there are some improvements that can be made to the audit service. It looks like the service scans through the pull request comments and the pull request review comments. If any comments are present (and not by the PR author) then the pull request is considered reviewed.

See https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/200f9154a9956283eb16ce01b4c5aa16b43b4d5a/api-audit/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/AuditServiceImpl.java#L290-L311

There are a couple of improvements that can be made:

A pull request review has a state. I see the states "PENDING", "APPROVED", "DISMISSED". There should also be a "Request Changes" status but I don't know is the corresponding API state. I think the service should be checking the state of the pull request review instead of looking at the review comments. The current implementation will accept "Pending" or "Request Changes" pull request reviews. That seems wrong. Here's the GitHub API: https://developer.github.com/v3/pulls/reviews/#get-a-single-review

There are external services that provide approval management. For example, Hygieia uses https://github.com/lgtmco/lgtm. It would be useful to allow a repository to configure Hygieia to recognize these services for approval management. These services work by setting a git commit status. The repository could register the status context with Hygieia, such as "approvals/lgtm" and that status check could be tested. https://developer.github.com/v3/repos/statuses/#list-statuses-for-a-specific-ref

Currently the audit service tests for the presence of any pull request comments. This doesn't seem like the correct behavior. For example, I could make a comment "Don't merge this. There's a NullPointerException on line 10" and that would be considered as peer review. I would remove the testing of pull request comments. Another option is to reproduce the functionality of a service like https://github.com/lgtmco/lgtm. It's a non-trivial implementation to reproduce that functionality.

I'm happy to submit pull requests on any of the three comments above. Just wanted to get feedback before I start writing code.
column5: Audit service improvements
column11:
334242725 I'm working on some improvements to audit an external service such as LGTM. Let's talk about them in a less public venue. mspiegel
334243352 We are just starting to build this... it is not solid yet - not sure what broken means if it is not solid :-)
Confirming one thing clearly - we are tools/process/method agnostic.
 tabladrum
334260757 @mspiegel Current state, all actors have ability to turn on/off lgtm as well as github protected branches.  We can reduce the amount of potential malicious actors by restricting who can alter github protected branches.  And that someone should maybe be a single release engineer or someone who isn't contributing directly to the repo.  

In the end, you're still going to need to trust *SOMEONE* with admin access to these tools.  I don't believe anyone can code a way around a people problem.

I totally agree malicious actors should be addressed, but I feel current state of peer review checking doesn't allow for all cases of valid peer review (I was originally going to open an issue here because I found the same exact block of code you did). poemdexter
334432267 @tabladrum @poemdexter @mspiegel @jdamick Thank you for the inputs and feedback. We will research it further and put in improvements. satishc1
335835805 I'm going to make an attempt and incorporating the changes above. I'll submit a PR mspiegel
331474748 Great feedback. Agree with (a) checking PR state. 
(b) We discussed the option of checking status of approval management hook. The problem is doing so is that those hooks can be turned off by a repo owner and turned back on after some direct commits to the branch by-passing PR mechanism and we won't know about it. There is a solution but may be a little overkill - we will need to trap into GH event stream. (c) We discussed this too. From a review comment perspective, a text saying "LGTM" is as good as "I am merging it anyway". IMO the correct way to do this would be to use some light weight sentiment analysis on the review comments and that itself will open up a good set of analytics points. 

Thoughts?
 tabladrum
331487409 On (b) I think only the repository administrators can enable or disable a service hook. I think you have to trust the repository admins. For example, the admins are the ones who can enable or disable a protected branch in GitHub. They are also the ones who decide whether or not admins can commit directly to a protected branch. So I think they have the equivalent or superuser or root access to the repository.

On (c) looking for the comment string "LGTM" would be an improvement over the current implementation. Sentiment analysis seems overkill IMO.  mspiegel
331487993 The admins can also rewrite history on a protected branch, if they allow admins to commit directly to the branch. mspiegel
331904548 yeah i would say you need to have trust at some level, so i would vote for (b) rather than (c) which would likely be a never ending stream of keyword matching or sentiment analysis.. jdamick
331909189 We should be able to support any code review process - LGTM, GH's own or anything else. tabladrum
334035750 Is there consensus on taking this course of action?
- use the GitHub API to check the GitHub Pull Request Review status?
- use the GitHub API to check the GitHub status checks for LGTM? 

I can submit a patch with these changes once we have consensus on what it needs to look like. Currently on master if someone types a comment "This pull request has a bug please don't merge it" the AuditStatus.PULLREQ_REVIEWED_BY_PEER status is set.  mspiegel
334159174 Are we expecting this to work only with LGTM -i.e. detecting LGTM webhook etc? Or are we saying we will look for the word "LGTM" in the review comment? If it is the second one, I am concerned about this review comment "This pull request does not LGTM". If it is the first one, how do we make it work with other review tools including GH review? tabladrum
334234463 I've received confirmation from several people that the LGTM tool is not required for SOD or PAR so we shouldn't rely on it too heavily.  The github API should be checked for review status and then maybe rely on LGTM comments afterwards.  Also LGTM can be turned off just as easily as protected branches in Github.  poemdexter
334235608 Another thing to think about is the fact that many teams rely on the maven release plugin to handle versioning.  Every release creates 2 additional commits directly on the release branch changing the pom versioning. poemdexter
334236378 Those commits are marked as such so that they are excluded (need to confirm @satishc1 about the exclusions) from this. tabladrum
334238224 I've come across another team as well that creates commits as part of their release due to the fact that maven release plugin requires git to show no outstanding changes.  So this would be ignoring commits directly to release due to some build step as well as maven release plugin.

Overall, I feel like Github can easily be configured to control peer reviews and it's strange to see devs have full admin access to repos they commit to as part of a larger team. poemdexter
334239145 Send me (via offline) an example of such commit.  tabladrum
334242208 There are two approaches to enforcing peer review. The first is to use the GitHub Pull Request Review feature and to check the box on the protected branch that requires a PR Review. The second is to use an external service such as the LGTM service and use a GitHub status check. Both approaches are valid. Using an external service can provide additional features that are not (currently) available in the GitHub Pull Request Review. For example, if you want to mandate a specific set of people to be reviewers. Or you want to require two or more reviewers for your pull request. Or you want to require that the author of the pull request is in the group of people who have signed a contributor license agreement.

What I'm requesting is that Hygieia support both of these approaches. I haven't had a second person confirm this, but it looks like the current implementation in Hygieia is broken? It just looks for the presence of comments. It doesn't test the GitHub Review API to check that the review was approved.

None of these these approaches address the issue of a malicious actor. The current implementation in Hygieia also doesn't address this question. I've been investigating some alternatives to solve that problem. Is that not a separate issue to be addressed? Can we first improve the current Hygieia peer review service? mspiegel
334242725 I'm working on some improvements to audit an external service such as LGTM. Let's talk about them in a less public venue. mspiegel
334243352 We are just starting to build this... it is not solid yet - not sure what broken means if it is not solid :-)
Confirming one thing clearly - we are tools/process/method agnostic.
 tabladrum
334260757 @mspiegel Current state, all actors have ability to turn on/off lgtm as well as github protected branches.  We can reduce the amount of potential malicious actors by restricting who can alter github protected branches.  And that someone should maybe be a single release engineer or someone who isn't contributing directly to the repo.  

In the end, you're still going to need to trust *SOMEONE* with admin access to these tools.  I don't believe anyone can code a way around a people problem.

I totally agree malicious actors should be addressed, but I feel current state of peer review checking doesn't allow for all cases of valid peer review (I was originally going to open an issue here because I found the same exact block of code you did). poemdexter
334432267 @tabladrum @poemdexter @mspiegel @jdamick Thank you for the inputs and feedback. We will research it further and put in improvements. satishc1

404208573 Hi

we had the same error with TDS server as Nithin had

`message=[LDAP: error code 53 - Unwilling To Perform]; nested exception is javax.naming.OperationNotSupportedException: [LDAP: error code 53 - Unwilling To Perform];`

the work around mentioned by @justinzyw works . In application.properties I set the following

`auth.authenticationProviders=STANDARD,LDAP
auth.ldapServerUrl=ldap://ldapserver:389/dc=company,dc=org

auth.ldapUserDnPattern=uid={0}
`

----------------------------------------------------

**To set bind user and password**

Note: we did not have to do the below to get ldap to work but during process of debugging, i could set userDn for binding by editing api module class com.capitalone.dashboard.config.WebSecurityConfig.configureLdap((AuthenticationManagerBuilder auth)) method as follows

`private void configureLdap(AuthenticationManagerBuilder auth) throws Exception {
        String ldapServerUrl = authProperties.getLdapServerUrl();
		String ldapUserDnPattern = authProperties.getLdapUserDnPattern();
		if (StringUtils.isNotBlank(ldapServerUrl) && StringUtils.isNotBlank(ldapUserDnPattern)) {
			
		       ContextSourceBuilder cbuild =auth.ldapAuthentication()
			.userDnPatterns(ldapUserDnPattern)
			.contextSource().url(ldapServerUrl);

                        cbuild.managerDn("cn=user1,dc=company,dc=org");
			
			cbuild.managerPassword("Password");
`

I have hard coded the user and password here but you may move it to applications,properties to be read by authProperties

Thanks
Sibi

Hi  there,

We are using Sonar 5.6.6.

I'm trying to link up Sonar on our Hygieia dashboard but can't find our project in the widget dropdown list, eventhough it is available at `http://sonar_address:9000/sonar/overview?id=com.xxx.xxx.xxx%3Aartifact-name`

After digging into the code a bit, I see that the Sonar collector fetches projects from `http://sonar_address:9000/sonar/api/resources?format=json`

And when I goto that address, lo and behold our project is not there either.

My question is, how to I configure this project to show up under /api/resources?

Thanks,
Ed

Hello, 
Would like to know why Docker compose file shows all environment properties commented out for all collector? 
Where and which file need to modify/update for individual collector ? adding them in Docker compose will override individual docker file collectors ?   Pls advise. 
 
Below is an example of Jenkins-build-collector from docker compose. 
------------------
hygieia-jenkins-build-collector:
  image: hygieia-jenkins-build-collector:latest
  container_name: hygieia-jenkins-build
  volumes:
  - ./logs:/hygieia/logs
  links:
  - mongodb:mongo
  - hygieia-api
#  environment:
#Jenkins server (required) - Can provide multiple
#  - JENKINS_MASTER=ttp://jenkins.company.com
#If using username/token for api authentication (required for Cloudbees Jenkins Ops Center) see sample
#  - JENKINS_OP_CENTER=http://username:token@jenkins.company.com
#Another option: If using same username/password Jenkins auth - set username/apiKey to use HTTP Basic Auth (blank=no auth)
#  - JENKINS_USERNAME
#  - JENKINS_API_KEY
#  - JENKINS_CRON=0 0/5 * * * *
#Determines if build console log is collected - defaults to false
#  - JENKINS_SAVE_LOG=true
column5: Docker compose file shows all environment properties commented out for all collector?
column11:
334155903 @rajeshksingh15 By default, Compose reads two files, a docker-compose.yml and an optional docker-compose.override.yml file. By convention, the docker-compose.yml contains your base configuration. The override file, overrides for existing configuration or adds new configuration.
You can create a docker-compose.override.yml and add the environment properties for Jenkins.

When  environment configuration is provided both in yml file and the Dockerfile ENV, the value from yml will be taken first. asg247

328001396 @sujaydevops1  -  At present, we have below ways to identify your job based on nicename , in your case nice name is Org name. 

If using Jenkins collector, specify nice name for your jenkins server as below in your jenkins properties. You can specify nice names for all servers based on indexing.  In your case, you can specify customized nice name for your jenkins instance and that should help you find the correct job. This route should work for you.

Eg: jenkins.servers[0]=http://***jenkins.com/job/folder_level/
       jenkins.niceNames[0]= give nice name here 

If using Hygieia plugin in Jenkins, you can specify server name in Jenkins -> Manage Configuration-> Global settings 
     Specify server name field - give nice name here - which is what you are doing now. This does not help much if you wan

While configuring dashboard - build wiget, you can search with format - nicename : jobname 
In you case - nice name (mentioned in prop file) : develop. 

Please update to latest code base as now the delimiter is ":" and not "-"
 nireeshT

     Specify server name field - give nice name here - which is what you are doing now. This does not help much if you wan

While configuring dashboard - build wiget, you can search with format - nicename : jobname 
In you case - nice name (mentioned in prop file) : develop. 

Please update to latest code base as now the delimiter is ":" and not "-"
 nireeshT

column2:
A blind mount allows you to overwrite the contents of an existing directory in docker. This PR moves the properties files for each docker image to a separate /config folder. This allows the config folder to be mounted to use config files on the local file system by setting SKIP_PROPERTIES_BUILDER=true. Doing so is advantageous as it is more flexible and powerful and because the docker properties builders often are overlooked when new properties are added.

I also fixed a part of #1207 that was missed - the ENC() block should not be in the default docker images. Since it was in hygieia-api it requires all images to use jasypt with no way to disable it. To use jasypt nothing changes - pass in / store in a compose file a JASYPT_ENCRYPTOR_PASSWORD and the property encrypted with ENC().

This also includes changes from #1674 as I needed to update that as well for this.

Docker blind mounts: https://docs.docker.com/engine/admin/volumes/bind-mounts/

Example:
```
  hygieia-api:
    image: hygieia-api:latest
    container_name: hygieia-api
    ports:
    - "8080:8080"
    volumes:
    - ./logs:/hygieia/logs
    - ./config:/hygieia/config
    environment:
    - MONGO_PORT=tcp://10.0.2.2:27017
    - SKIP_PROPERTIES_BUILDER=true
```

```
$ ls config
hygieia-api.properties                                
hygieia-appdynamics-performance-collector.properties  
hygieia-artifactory-artifact-collector.properties     
hygieia-bitbucket-scm-collector.properties            
hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties
hygieia-jira-feature-collector.properties
hygieia-sonar-codequality-collector.properties
hygieia-xldeploy-deployment-collector.properties
```

You can also achieve the same using docker run passing in environment variables and a mount.
column5: Move docker config file location to allow for mounting configs
column11:
350310321 @MarkRx, I'm currently reviewing this PR and I have a couple of concerns. First off, I think it's a really good idea to pass in a properties file instead of using env vars to create a properties file at run-time. That being said, I've ran into some issues.
- 1: I'm currently using Docker For Mac version 17.09.0-ce and have mounted my config folder as you have suggested in your example, but unfortunately it seems that the folder is mounted too late in the container creation process and therefore isn't present when the last line of the Dockerfile is executed. So with a compose entry like this:
```
hygieia-api:
  image: hygieia-api:latest
  volumes:
  - ./logs:/hygieia/logs
  - ./config:/hygieia/config
  environment:
    - SKIP_PROPERTIES_BUILDER=true
```
and running `docker-compose up` no config is loaded since the properties builder doesn't run and the volume isn't mounted yet. As far as I can tell the only way we can get the properties file loaded in time is by modifying the Dockerfile to COPY the file over.
- 2: This issue isn't as much of a deal breaker, but still a problem. You used $MONGO_HOST and $MONGO_PORT. These are only available when using [legacy container linking](https://docs.docker.com/engine/userguide/networking/default_network/dockerlinks/) which is a problem in that it we will have to take it out later when we introduce networks and we **will** have to introduce networks at some point. Especially if we ever want to run our containers in production. So changing the names of these env vars really isn't that big of a deal since there isn't really a standard but we shouldn't assume that Mongo is always going to provide these for us.

Here's an example of the env sharing present when using linking but missing using a network:
```
# save this as links.yml
# run 'docker-compose -f links.yml up | grep alpine'
# env vars are shared when using legacy container linking
mongo:
  image: mongo

alpine:
  image: alpine
  command: env
  links:
    - mongo:mongo
```

```
# save this as network.yml
# run 'docker-compose -f network.yml up | grep alpine'
# with networks there is no env var sharing
version: "3"

services:
  mongo: 
    image: mongo
    networks:
      - my-network

  alpine:
    image: alpine
    command: env
    networks:
      - my-network

networks:
  my-network:
```
In the logs you'll notice the vars present for the linked example but not for the networked one
 matthewbeasley
357722905 Thank you @MarkRx @matthewbeasley  satishc1
357722985 @tabladrum LGTM satishc1

Could not get the data to populate on the UI...no errors in logs or console....super annoying.  I finally just decided to debugged the collector on my day off, for fun. 
Low and behold: /api/project_analyses/search?project used in DefaultSonar6Client does not appear in the API until 6.3 and the collector eats the error instead of letting you know.


Simple solution, just say your version is 5.9.  This switches the client to the older one. (well mostly populating.....the unit test stuff is not populating, but I am not sure if that is my sonarQB set up or another bug..will save that for the weekend.  If it turns out to be another bug will add info for that here)

Hope this helps others.

Also I won't be able to submit an update to the readme for sometime due to our review policy around committing to open sources.  If anyone else wants to do so, my thanks.

column2:
First of all thank you committers for managing such beautiful and a complex project.
Came across to this recently and started playing with it. Have some minor feedbacks for the improvements however the major pain point I faced was rebuilding the whole application stack. Which takes quiet some time to finish given the size of the code base.

I have some idea of improving the build time.Its like this:
  Application is composed of building the api.jar and then docker image. What we can do is to separate out the these two steps. Once we do it, the framework part (mostly api.jar) will not be rebuild and instead can be pulled from the maven artifactory (or we can pull it from this gitrepo via maven build process). Now most of our efforts will be used in building the image and not the api.jar.

In case some users need to create custom collectors/connectors, they can easily do in the second maven based project which builds docker image by leveraging packages from api.jar.

The same refactoring can be done for UI.

Let me know what you guys feel about it. I would love to hear your wise feedbacks.

thanks.

In order to accomplish this, simply navigate to the directory of the component you would like to build (e.g api) and then run `mvn clean install` or `mvn clean install docker:build` if you want docker images. This will build only the desired module. matthewbeasley

The EncryptionController.encrypt method only accepts GET which results in passwords (e.g. when setting up the Bitbucket collector) being visible in the access log.

Enforcing POST would make sure passwords are not visible in the access logs.

column2: The big change here is moving "teamId" from a path param to a query param.  Gitlab has a concept of subgroups, and the subgroups are delimited by "/".  You can't send a "/" as a path param obviously, and url encoding it is still not accepted by most servers unless explicitly turned on.  The other change was moving the query parameters in the angular app into an object, instead of doing string manipulation which is very brittle.

column2:
My application.properties file -

# Database Name
dbname=dashboard

# Database Username - default is blank
dbusername=dashboarduser

# Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=dbpassword

# Database HostName - default is localhost
dbhost=localhost

# Database Port - default is 27017
dbport=27017

# MongoDB replicaset
dbreplicaset=false
dbhostport=localhost:27017,127.0.0.1:27017,ip-172-31-26-184:27017

# Logging File location
logging.file=./logs/jira.log

# PageSize - Expand contract this value depending on Jira implementation's
# default server timeout setting (You will likely receive a SocketTimeoutException)
feature.pageSize=100

# Delta change date that modulates the collector item task
# Occasionally, these values should be modified if database size is a concern
feature.deltaStartDate=2017-03-01T00:00:00.000000
feature.masterStartDate=2017-03-01T00:00:00.000000
feature.deltaCollectorItemStartDate=2017-03-01T00:00:00.000000

# Chron schedule: S M D M Y [Day of the Week]
feature.cron=0 * * * * *

# ST Query File Details - Required, but DO NOT MODIFY
#In-built folder housing prepared REST queries (required)
feature.queryFolder=jiraapi-queries

feature.storyQuery=story
feature.epicQuery=epic
feature.projectQuery=projectinfo
feature.memberQuery=memberinfo
feature.sprintQuery=sprintinfo
feature.teamQuery=teaminfo
feature.trendingQuery=trendinginfo

#feature.sprintDays=60
#feature.sprintEndPrior=7
#feature.scheduledPriorMin=2

# JIRA CONNECTION DETAILS:
# Enterprise Proxy - ONLY INCLUDE IF YOU HAVE A PROXY
#feature.jiraProxyUrl=http://proxy.com
#feature.jiraProxyPort=9000

feature.jiraBaseUrl=jira url
feature.jiraQueryEndpoint=rest/api/2/

column5: How  to start the UI in 2.0.4
column11:
324846276 I resolved this issue finally.
my solution is as following.
step1, use non-root user, to the project-root directory
 cd /home/yangqian/Hygieia-2.0.4
 sudo chmod -R 777 ./Hygieia-2.0.4
 then mvn clean package -pl UI docker:build
  results:the docker will failed, 

step2, go to /home/yangqian/Hygieia-2.0.4/UI/node_modules/gulp/bin
with root user
node gulp serve

result:server is up.

My questions:which use should we use to execute "mvn clean package -pl UI docker:build", where and which user should we use to execute "node gulp serve".

Thank you! yqbjtu

column5: Need information on Hygieia Setup
column11:
324757931 The best way I would say to do it is through the docker-compose.yml file. Build the individual docker images and just do a "docker-compose up". Keep the docker-compose.yml file only for the db,API and UI layers and override it with a docker-compose.override.yml for the individual collectors. You might need to tweak the files a little bit to get it to work. It is not the most smoothest docker setup that I have seen. srinathanand

Properties file - 

```
# Database Name
dbname=dashboarddb
# Database HostName - default is localhost
dbhost=localhost
# Database Port - default is 27017
dbport=27017
# MongoDB replicaset
dbreplicaset=false 
dbhostport=localhost:27017,127.0.0.1:27017,ip-172-31-26-184:27017
# Database Username - default is blank
dbusername=dashboarduser
# Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=dbpassword
# Collector schedule (required)
jenkins-codequality.cron=0 0/1 * * * *
# Collector servers (required) - can be multiple
jenkins-codequality.servers[0]=http://psumanaratne:83212caf8b414b89a4f9c4fdf87d3711@localhost:8082/jenkins
#jenkins-codequality.servers[0]=http://localhost:8082/jenkins
# Collector types (note not required, but the regex should be match only the type specified)
jenkins-codequality.artifactRegex.junit=TEST-.*\\.xml
jenkins-codequality.artifactRegex.findbugs=findbugsXml.xml
jenkins-codequality.artifactRegex.pmd=pmd.xml
jenkins-codequality.artifactRegex.checkstyle=checkstyle-result.xml
jenkins-codequality.artifactRegex.jacoco=jacoco.xml
# Collector job depth (required) should be set to at least 1, and more if you use folder jobs etc
jenkins-codequality.jobDepth=4
```
Command - 

`java -jar jenkins-codequality-2.0.5-SNAPSHOT.jar --spring.config.location=..\jenkinsCQ.properties`
inside target folder.

I'm pretty sure it uses the properties file, since its connecting to the correct DB. So there's no problem with the command, must be something wrong with the properties file.

column2: The configuration for the gitlab feature collector didn't really make sense as it was.  This pull request changes how a user configures a gitlab feature collector to inputting a group and project, instead of selecting from a list. ```

 jenkins-codequality.artifactRegex.junit=TEST-.*\\.xml

jenkins-codequality.jobDepth=4

I have a job with unit tests that's been built a few times in my Jenkins instance..

setup DB
Created new database "dashboard"

# This is my mongod.conf
systemLog:
  destination: file
  logAppend: true
  path: /opt/mount/apisrvc/mongodb/log/mongod.log
storage:
  dbPath: /opt/mount/apisrvc/mongodb/data/db1
  journal:
    enabled: true
processManagement:
  fork: true  # fork and run in background
  pidFilePath: /opt/mount/apisrvc/mongodb/mongod.pid  # location of pidfile
net:
  port: 27017
  bindIp: 127.0.0.1  # Listen to local interface only, comment to listen on all interfaces.

Build the entire application from root
change to directory /opt/mount/apisrvc/Hygieia
execute the following mvn clean install package
Build succeeds

Build the project/core
change to directory /opt/mount/apisrvc/Hygieia/core
execute mvn install
build succeeds

Build and run the API
change to directory /opt/mount/apisrvc/Hygieia/api
execute mvn install
build succeeds
execute 
nohup java -jar target/api.jar --spring.config.name=api --spring.config.location=dashboard.properties & >/dev/null
api monitoring starts

# This is my dashboard.properties for api
dbname=dashboard
dbusername=hyadmin
dbpassword=xxxxxxx
dbhost=localhost
dbport=27017
dbreplicaset=false
dbhostport=localhost:27017,127.0.0.1:27017
server.contextPath=/api
server.port=8080
corsEnabled=false
auth.expirationTime=10

Build and run the UI

execute mvn install
build succeeds
execute gulp serve
hygieia login page opens at localhost:3000

change to directory /opt/mount/apisrvc/Hygieia/collectors/build/jenkins
execute mvn install
build succeeds
execute
